<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: WESTMINSTER; SCHOOL EMPLOYEE WINS STATE AWARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JON NALICK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Westminster School District employee has won a prestigious award honoring 
his work promoting the merit system statewide. 
</P>
<P>
 The California School Personnel Commissioners Assn. recently awarded John L. 
Woodie the Schuyler C. Joyner Award. 
</P>
<P>
 The award, named for the man who pressed for the nation's first school merit 
system law, has been given each year since 1977, said district spokeswoman 
Audrey Brown. 
</P>
<P>
 In merit system districts, employees and potential employees are recruited and 
promoted based on formal tests of their skills and knowledge. 
</P>
<P>
 Woodie, classified personnel director for Westminster School District, has 
served the district for 40 years and is a also a founding member of the 
California School Employees Assn. 
</P>
<P>
 He said he had not anticipated receiving the award. 
</P>
<P>
 " Surprise wasn't the word that came to mind at the time; I was shocked. 
Obviously, I'm very happy about it," Woodie said.JON NALICK 
</P>
</TEXT>
