<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SINGLES SENSATIONS OF THE LIFELONG BACHELOR; RELATIONSHIPS: AT 40, DOES A 
NEVER-MARRIED HETEROSEXUAL HAVE TO EXPLAIN HIMSELF? COUNSELORS THEORIZE AS 
O.C.'S AVAILABLE GET SET IN THEIR WAYS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK MOTT, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Once, being a never-married bachelor entering middle age was considered to be 
a pretty good gig. There were romantic role models: the sophisticated Henry 
Higgins, the dashing James Bond. That all-time good guy, Superman. 
</P>
<P>
 Lifelong bachelors, at 40, were considered rugged individualists, urbane, 
worldly, self-aware, blissfully free, with unlimited options. They were even 
objects of envy. 
</P>
<P>
 Today, the thought of a never-married, heterosexual man at age 40 produces a 
predictable reaction, but that reaction is usually worded this way: 
</P>
<P>
 "There must be something wrong with him." 
</P>
<P>
 Perhaps exacerbated by a culture in which various degrees of male-bashing have 
flourished in recent years, the idea that the never-married middle-aged man is 
somehow dysfunctional appears to have gained more than just a toehold. Is he a 
commitment-phobic? Is he a mama's boy? Is he emotionally stunted? Is he 
sexually immature? Is he a woman-hater? 
</P>
<P>
 Surely there must be something wrong with him? 
</P>
<P>
 Not so, says Charles Waehler, a psychologist at the University of Akron in 
Ohio, who conducted a study of never-married men over age 40 in 1991. The 
study, limited to white, heterosexual men, concluded that half were happy, 
successful and satisfied and the other half, while somewhat disturbed by their 
bachelor status, were too set in their ways to risk marriage. 
</P>
<P>
 This may account for the fairly large number of never-married men over 40 that 
appear in the 1990 United States Census as well as in Waehler's studies. 
</P>
<P>
 According to the census, 10.5% of white men age 40 to 44 have never married -- 
up from 7.1% in 1980. The data also show never-married black men 40 and older 
to be about twice as likely as white men to stay single. 
</P>
<P>
 A never-married status for heterosexual men at that age can be attributable to 
many reasons. 
</P>
<P>
 "I certainly have nothing against marriage," said Lansing Young, 39, a teacher 
and athletics coach at Whittier High School, "and I'm not putting it completely 
out of the question. But I still feel like I'm 18. I don't feel I've changed 
that much. 
</P>
<P>
 "I like kids very much, and I think kids of my own might be interesting, and I 
think I'd probably make a good father, but I'd probably make a bad husband. 
I've lived by myself for so long; I'm pretty set in my ways and self-centered. 
A woman might have a hard time putting up with that for a long time." 
</P>
<P>
 Young said he had an "off-and-on" relationship for about five years when he 
was in his 20s and another that lasted about a year and a half. There is no 
woman in his life at the moment. 
</P>
<P>
 He said he has never been closely questioned or ridiculed about his bachelor 
status and said that if he were, "I'd probably think it was kind of comical. If 
someone ridiculed me for not being married, I'd wonder what was wrong with 
them. They don't know what my life is like." 
</P>
<P>
 He says he dates infrequently, but he said that is because he has "in the last 
few years become pretty particular about the type of woman I see. As the years 
have gone by, I've gotten much less impulsive. My brother-in-law's a divorce 
lawyer, too, and he's always said that if I ever think I might want to get 
married, to call him first, because there's a lot to lose." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Richard Caldwell, too, said his standards are particular, and that is mostly 
what accounts for his being a lifelong bachelor at age 57. Caldwell, a 
plastic-container manufacturer from Garden Grove, continues to date -- he is a 
member of Black Singles of Orange County -- but said he has met only one woman 
that he ever wanted to marry: a Japanese woman he met while serving in the 
military in Japan during his late 20s and early 30s. But he was discouraged by 
both military and Japanese authorities, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "When I came back to the states," he said, "I found that the women were so 
demanding," Caldwell said. "I was trying to find someone similar to the person 
I found overseas, and I just couldn't." 
</P>
<P>
 He was involved in one more long-term relationship, he said, and he is 
involved with a woman now whom he said might be a marriage prospect. And, he 
added, after many years of the single life, he'd still like to be married. 
</P>
<P>
 "I feel I've missed out on a part of life, dealing with another human being of 
a different gender who thinks differently than I do. It's good to have someone 
to sit down and be able to talk to and who will know you well as a human being. 
</P>
<P>
 "On the other hand, today I don't have to answer to anybody; I can come and go 
as I please. That's the advantage to being single." 
</P>
<P>
 That may not be enough of an explanation to suit many people who continue to 
see the never-married 40-year-old as a kind of social misfit, said Eugene 
Ericson, a clinical psychologist from Irvine who specializes in relationship 
counseling. 
</P>
<P>
 "Yeah, they're suspect," he said. "Occasionally, their personal dynamics may 
be such that they're just a bit shy and are comfortable with their current 
living situation and don't really venture out very much. But sometimes they're 
caught up in their work, and their work becomes their obsession. It's a matter 
of these people developing self-esteem, feeling self-worth and recognizing 
their emotional needs and how to get them fulfilled. More commonly, they're 
pretty repressed individuals, somewhat rigid and dogmatic and not flexible 
enough or emotional enough to establish a romantic bond." 
</P>
<P>
 That sort of talk, however, bothers Ben, who, at age 42, is a newlywed of 
seven months (he asked that his last name not be used). His previous lifelong 
bachelorhood had been anything but unfulfilling, he says. 
</P>
<P>
 "My wife used words like 'You're over 40 and never been married, so what's the 
matter with you?' more than once during our courtship. She figured that such a 
person was at the very least commitment-phobic, and there's probably a grain of 
truth to that. But what I told her then, and still believe, is that it's far 
better to wait than to marry young with little understanding of the qualities 
needed to make a marriage work, when people don't yet have the tools, nor the 
strength of character to reconcile the inevitable differences. 
</P>
<P>
 "When I was younger I thought that marriage only made sense if you wanted to 
have children, and though I knew I'd want a gaggle of kids at some point, I was 
simply never ready until recently. And though I've revised that view of 
marriage, there was still never any hurry. My dad fathered me when he was 51 
years old, and I certainly never experienced any drawbacks in that 
relationship. 
</P>
<P>
 "In any case, once I was ready to get married, well, I was ready to get 
married." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 John Paul Gray, a psychologist with practices in San Juan Capistrano and Santa 
Ana, says "My first question to a middle-aged man who has never married is, 
'have you had any long-term relationships?' If he hasn't been in such a 
relationship, I'd ask why he hasn't had that common experience that we expect 
someone of that age to have had." 
</P>
<P>
 However, said Gray, who conducts couples therapy, if the middle-aged man has 
had a number of long-term relationships in his life and remains single by 
choice, he may be perfectly healthy emotionally. 
</P>
<P>
 "Let's assume the guy has had the usual relationships," Gray said. "The 
primary task of recovering from a relationship is getting to be at home with 
yourself, getting comfortable and accepting yourself as your prime source of 
entertainment. Once you've learned that, you get to really like it. Once you 
hit that place, you can live alone, and many people do. But that's not 
something that happens overnight." 
</P>
<P>
 For some men, like Albert Frias, a 40-year-old public information officer for 
the Baldwin Park School District, their bachelor status is a matter of 
geography and economics. During his 20s and 30s, Frias said he hopscotched 
around the western United States, moving up the job and pay ladder, and felt 
that it would have been a strain on a potential marriage to be moving so much 
and making so little money. 
</P>
<P>
 "I knew it would be difficult to relocate if I was married," he said. "And at 
that time, there was no way that I'd be able to afford a wife and everything 
else." 
</P>
<P>
 The idea of marriage, he said, has not quite gone a-glimmering, but . . .  
</P>
<P>
 "Now that I've just turned 40," said Frias, who said he has been seeing 
someone off and on for about four years, "I'm pretty set in my ways, and I 
don't have a lot of tolerance like I used to. I don't put up with a lot. 
Marriage isn't something I think about much anymore. If it comes, it comes." 
</P>
<P>
 Psychologist Ericson said that the aging bachelor can change his status -- 
provided he wants to -- through the development of one laudable virtue. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'd tell them to get some courage," said Ericson, "and to live their lives in 
a different way. To live life like a warrior. Not to fight, but to live life 
bravely." 
</P>
</TEXT>
