<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: HEALTH CARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by James M. Gomez, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Bare Bones: Are you suffering from an overpowering desire to know just how 
human bones are formed? 
</P>
<P>
 If so, then ICN Biomedicals, a subsidiary of ICN Pharmaceuticals Inc., has 
just the chemical for you. 
</P>
<P>
 ICN Biomedicals said it is now selling tubulin, a protein that is a necessary 
component in cell structure and the formation of new cells. 
</P>
<P>
 So far so good. 
</P>
<P>
 But more importantly, ICN Biomedicals officials said, it is also a component 
of the human body that promotes bone, cartilage and connective tissue growth. 
</P>
<P>
 Tubulin will be sold by laboratories involved in trying to discover how those 
bodily systems work -- or rather don't work. By understanding how bones and 
other parts of the body work properly, researchers hope to ultimately 
understand how they become cancerous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
