<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: HEALTH CARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by James M. Gomez, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Breathing Easier: A pair of former Orange County hospital executives have 
decided to go it alone to market a new laser surgery procedure that can ease 
problems associated with lung disease in smokers. 
</P>
<P>
 John Kramer and Linda Simons, both of whom recently worked at Chapman General 
Hospital in Orange, started U.S. Lung Centers of Yorba Linda.The firm will be 
promoting a surgical technique called thoracoscopic laser bullectomy. The 
procedure, performed after a tiny incision is made in the chest, is used to 
treat bullous emphysema, a disease in which air cysts are formed in the lungs, 
impeding breathing. The condition is acute in smokers. 
</P>
<P>
 The firm has already garnered a contract with doctors at Western Medical 
Center-Santa Ana. U.S. Lung Centers will manage the hospital's lung center and 
market the procedure to the community. Terms of the contract were not 
disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
